Title: Sources of Selection in Strategy Making 
Author-Name: J. Ignacio Canales  
Abstract:
  This paper elaborates theory inductively by following the evolution of 14
 strategic initiatives from an exploratory case study. The study examines
 the context and character of such initiatives over an 8-year period. Based
 on these initiatives, the paper proposes a two-stage selection mechanism
 for the intra-evolutionary strategy process that explains the long-term
 mutation of organizations. The mechanism operates by selecting according
 to both fit with the strategic intent and feasibility of the initiative.
 These two elements combine into an organizational principle that is
 perceived as permanent in character but mutates through constructive
 confrontation. This principle contributes to the organizational identity
 but, being a low-level element of such identity, it can be modified
 through learning while retaining an attribute of endurance as perceived by
 organizational members. 
