Title: Changing Routine: Reframing Performance Management within a Multinational 
Author-Name: Philip Stiles  
Author-Name: Jonathan Trevor  
Author-Name: Elaine Farndale  
Author-Name: Shad S. Morris  
Author-Name: Jaap Paauwe  
Author-Name: Guenter Stahl  
Author-Name: Patrick Wright  
Abstract:
  This paper seeks to extend the literature on how change occurs in
 organizational routines by examining the link between routines and
 schemata and showing the cognitive and motivational factors involved.
 Using an in-depth analysis of a Japanese multinational, we develop an
 account of how a newly-implemented centralized performance management
 routine is interpreted by managers at two subsidiaries. We show how
 different performances of subroutines emerge into a new ostensive pattern
 of a routine, and how the cognitive and motivational aspects of individual
 agency are manifested in this process and how they affect the espoused
 organizational schema. 
